  "prompt": "Which is the best book for maths?",
  "response": "There isn't a single \"best\" book for mathematics, as the ideal book depends on your level of expertise, interests, and the specific area of mathematics you are studying. However, here are some highly regarded books across various levels and fields:\n\n1. **For High School Mathematics:**\n   - \"The Art of Problem Solving\" series by Richard Rusczyk and others\n   - \"Precalculus\" by Michael Sullivan\n   - \"Calculus\" by James Stewart\n\n2. **For Undergraduate Level:**\n   - \"Calculus\" by Michael Spivak\n   - \"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler\n   - \"Abstract Algebra\" by David S. Dummit and Richard M. Foote\n   - \"Introduction to Probability\" by Dimitri P. Bertsekas and John N. Tsitsiklis\n\n3. **For Graduate Level:**\n   - \"Principles of Mathematical Analysis\" by Walter Rudin\n   - \"Algebra\" by Serge Lang\n   - \"Topology\" by James Munkres\n   - \"Measure Theory\" by Paul R. Halmos\n\n4. **For Recreational Mathematics:**\n   - \"The Joy of x: A Guided Tour of Math, from One to Infinity\" by Steven Strogatz\n   - \"G\u00f6del, Escher, Bach: An Eternal Golden Braid\" by Douglas Hofstadter\n   - \"The Mathematical Experience\" by Philip J. Davis and Reuben Hersh\n\n5. **For Applied Mathematics:**\n   - \"Numerical Recipes: The Art of Scientific Computing\" by William H. Press, Saul A. Teukolsky, William T. Vetterling, and Brian P. Flannery\n   - \"Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning\" by Christopher M. Bishop\n   - \"Partial Differential Equations\" by Lawrence C. Evans\n\nChoosing the best book also depends on your learning style, whether you prefer rigorous proofs and theory or a more applied approach with practical examples.",
